Text.Value: That was so well-played, I'm not even mad.
No wonder I didn't remember you. You have such a dull face.
Your face is pretty bland too.
Who is Disciple Balthazar?
You know, you should go check on them - just in case.
A pity I am in no mood for hide-and-seek.
I'm glad I snuck the prisoners out when I did.
Not a chance.
Seen what coming?

EditorData.NodeContext: mocking shrug. She has the gold but is pretending otherwise

Text.Value: You have the same black-tongued sense of humour as ever, I don't believe you for a heartbeat.
I can take care of them, if you wish.
*Her smirk hides her intent - she's toying with you.*
But this is no less than what I deserve for failing Her.

EditorData.NodeContext: sad, dissapointed in herself, thought she was better

Text.Value: I'm looking for a particular prisoner - Duke Ravengard?
You. Not you. Lord Ketheric may think you pose no threat to him in your disgrace, but I know the things you've done.
Why tame a wild horse when it's so close to breaking its own spirit?
Ha... hahaha.

EditorData.NodeContext: an almost hysterical laugh as the player confesses to helping prisoners escape

Text.Value: And if I do talk to them?
Good day to you, True Soul.
He is chief advisor to General Ketheric and one of the Absolute's favoured. His necromancy is second only to the General's - it is an honour to serve him.
Indeed, but all are kept out of reach and under constant surveillance in the office above. Prison security is my highest priority.

EditorData.NodeContext: gravely serious, with a note of pride

Text.Value: No need. Once they realise escape is impossible, the Absolute will extend Her hand - and they will accept.
You thief - give me back my gold.
Do not disrespect me - I am a True Soul.
Z'rell herself has entrusted me with an important mission.
Whatever happened in the past is irrelevant now.
I'm Ketheric's new favourite.
Your name, your place was kept from all of us last time, but you were to be shown the utmost of respect.
The floor is yours, but stay your tongue. Do not speak to those behind bars.
What gold?

EditorData.NodeContext: mocking shrug. She has the gold but is pretending otherwise

Text.Value: You spark of the familiar. Do I know you, True Soul?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Looking over the player with a curious glance

Text.Value: Arcana runs through my veins - my magic is as powerful as it is tempestuous.
Arcana runs through my veins - I am a sorcerer.
Have you considered they might be shaking from laughter? Just a thought.

EditorData.NodeContext: playful smirk as she looks the player over - mocking them

Text.Value: I'll speak to them if I want.
You don't look very busy to me.
Move along, True Soul - have a pleasant day.
Leave.
So you can read? Congratulations.
How in the Hells do you know me?
Pity - I was about to grant you an exception.
*Your mind swirls with information about the prison: the small levers behind the Warden's desk open every cell, while the larger one triggers the alarm.*
The Absolute shines upon me. She tests me - then She gifts me you. I will now rip you apart - in Her name.

EditorData.NodeContext: zealous, relieved - about to attack player

Text.Value: Not as impressive as you. It is rare to find someone so singularly devoted to a task.
There will be no trial, no jury. I will split you from head to heel - and the Absolute will thank me for it.

EditorData.NodeContext: threatening the player - smile as she imagines it

Text.Value: He sounds important, and I'm afraid the mere dregs are the only ones left in my care.

EditorData.NodeContext: smirk, thinking of the prisoners she is currently tormenting

Text.Value: Pockets running a little empty, are they?
Leave.
You must confiscate lots of interesting things from prisoners.
A pity you're already failing then.
They're not leaving here alive - let them learn it the hard way.
I am a busy woman, True Soul. What is it?
The rules don't apply to me.
Gently probe the Warden's mind.
Why ban speaking to prisoners?
I should have seen that coming.
Actually, never mind. I'll leave the prisoners be.
I didn't know he had such... refined taste.

EditorData.NodeContext: Looking at player - sarcasm. She's completely unimpressed with them.

Text.Value: You're not going to stop them?
Farewell, True Soul. Serve Her well.

EditorData.NodeContext: knows she'll be killed soon - sounds resigned

Text.Value: They always think that.
That makes sense, True Soul - you clearly don't know the meaning of the word.

EditorData.NodeContext: a smile as she insults th eplayer

Text.Value: I know. We all know. Their 'whispers' are as subtle as a knife in the ear.
That sounds like a venereal disease.
Please try - I could use a laugh.
Disciple Balthazar has plans for them - and were I you I would not get in the way.
I burned down the grove.
Little good it'll do - no lockpick can breach the Absolute's domain. But watching them try is almost endearing.
Is that so? If you are above the General's chief advisor, you must be most impressive.

EditorData.NodeContext: Toying with the player, a little smirk - she thinks the player is an idiot.

Text.Value: You don't.
Oh, don't mind me. My brain is all but mincemeat - I'm harmless now!
I assumed you overstayed your welcome. Little did I expect you to intrude again.
If you're looking for a soft bed and warm fire, I have a cell that would suit you perfectly.

EditorData.NodeContext: saracasm - there is no soft bed and warm fire

Text.Value: I overheard the gnomes planning an escape.
Fine.  ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_6057ad05-9492-4630-9f0a-be548b134c54])
I'm actually Balthazar's closest confidante.
Kindly keep your fur and faeces to yourself.
I am a wizard - an expert in magic and all its mysteries.
As it should be.

EditorData.NodeContext: closes eyes briefly and sighs as she accepts her fate

Text.Value: I'm not here to play games - I need to speak to the prisoners. Now.
Regardless, know this - I am the Warden. The prisoners are my charges, and I answer to Disciple Balthazar himself. Stay on my good side.
My face might be bland, but yours? It is now carved into my memory - forever.
That tone might work on swaddled babes and puppies, but I am neither, True Soul.

EditorData.NodeContext: playful smirk - the player just tried to stand up to her, and she finds it most amusing.

Text.Value: I could regale you with tales of my daring deeds - and there are many. But I really must speak to the prisoners.
Oh, dear - does someone think they're important? You are small, True Soul, insignificant, and above all? Replaceable. Do not forget that.
Argh. You are no True Soul! I'll kill you, traitor.

EditorData.NodeContext: Vicious, about to get into combat?

Text.Value: Let them think they chose their fate - it is better, I find.
I was - for a time.
I could kill you, you know.
I didn't know setting fire to trees was so admirable.
A fool, perhaps, but a dangerous fool.
Anyone who refutes the Absolute is an enemy of mine, True Soul. You would do well to remember that.
I'm glad to be recognised by someone of such... staggering repute.
Please, you have to help me, I really don't know what's going on.
You set foot in our tower once. You did not leave, at least not through any door I have watch over.
Hm. Fascinating.

EditorData.NodeContext: Don't believe the player - bored sarcasm.

Text.Value: I am the fiercest warrior you'll ever meet. My enemies shake when they hear my roar.
I'll do my utmost to impress you.
I'm afraid none, no matter how generous, may speak to the prisoners.

EditorData.NodeContext: Smug and smirking - you've just taken the players gold and you're not giving it back

Text.Value: How about a large donation? ([GEN_CheckMagicPocketGold_2_463b0f43-5410-412d-aba3-875cf81c38ca])
Other tieflings, your own people, are in a cell. Aren't you bothered?
Our people suffered enough in Elturel - only to be locked up here, by one of their own. Aren't you bothered?
The Absolute thanks you for this generous donation, True Soul. You can go now.

EditorData.NodeContext: dismissive and also very pleased with yourself

Text.Value: Keep your bloody thoughts to yourself and your head down.
Do not be. It is fitting - I failed her. Try not to do the same.

EditorData.NodeContext: resigned, sad, a small spark of concern for the player

Text.Value: I'm a master of stealth and subterfuge.
I am dead.
...My, they are letting all sorts become a True Soul these days.
Whatever your business, a warning: none may speak to the prisoners - Disciple Balthazar was most clear.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dismissive expecting the player to leave now

Text.Value: You should see me in a fight - I can transform into powerful beasts from across the realms.
Respect you must have proven yourself unworthy of. And now you waste my time.
Careful. You may be a True Soul, but I will not hesitate to enforce Her will.

EditorData.NodeContext: smile as she threatens the player

Text.Value: I didn't know we were so hard-pressed for staff.
Is someone feeling rebellious, True Soul? Fine. Speak to them if you wish - but when I catch you, and I will catch you.

EditorData.NodeContext: smile as she threatens the player

Text.Value: I'm not sure why someone of your stature must converse with prisoners. Perhaps a small donation would convince me.

EditorData.NodeContext: playful smirk - you're actually planning to rob the player. Pause on 'convince' as she smiles

Text.Value: I am a paladin - my word is my bond. I have good reason to speak to the prisoners, I swear it.
Then you'll get your own cell.
Not the cheeriest greeting I've ever had.
I'm sure you do. Alas, I am not quite convinced. Perhaps a small donation would help.
*And interesting items confiscated from prisoners lie above the Warden's office, just up the ladder.*
A fair point. And they should remember who decides their fate - it will do them good.

EditorData.NodeContext: pleased with the idea and malicious

Text.Value: Disciple Balthazar's orders still stand - none may speak to the prisoners. You can go now.
No need. The scrying eyes are keeping watch, and my patrols can handle gnomes.

EditorData.NodeContext: mocking - particularly on gnomes. She thinks they're pathetic

Text.Value: You're not bothered that you'll be killed?
The prisoners have escaped - and the blame falls on me. I will be split open, my innards splayed before the eyes of the Absolute.
I heard you the first time.
You're going to tell me everything you know.
If you are going to stare, kindly do it elsewhere. As I said - you are free to roam where you wish, but do not speak to the prisoners.
I'm sorry.
Hm. Perhaps not - your face is rather bland.
Most wise, True Soul.

EditorData.NodeContext: Dismissive glance, nearly shooing them away

Synopsis: The Warden is a devout follower of the Absolute with an iron will, but also a sense of mischief. When the player approaches, she sees it as an opportunity to play with the player a little bit - like a cat with a mouse.
